\begin_layout Standard
We also investigate the second key aspect of imprecise quantum measurement,
 which is its statistical nature as reflected in the application of the
 Born rule determining the probability of a given measurement outcome
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983bibTeX,Mermin2007,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

.
 Here, Gleason's theorem establishes that there is no alternative to the
 Born rule by demonstrating, using reasonable continuity arguments in Hilbert
 spaces of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ge3$
\end_inset

, the existence of a unique state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 consistent with the statistical predictions computed from the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

.
 Our question then concerns what happens when infinite precision cannot
 be achieved.
 We are able to show that, while a QIVPM incorporating the effects of finite
 precision might not be consistent with Gleason's unique state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 on all projectors defined on a Hilbert space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Hilb$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ge3$
\end_inset

, there is a mathematically precise sense in which one recovers the original
 Gleason theorem asymptotically.
 Specifically, it is possible to construct a class of QIVPMs representing
 bounded resources that is parameterized by the size of the intervals.
 We then demonstrate that all QIVPMs in this class are consistent with a
 non-empty 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ball
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of quantum states whose radius is defined by the maximal length of the
 intervals characterizing the uncertainties.
 As the size of the intervals goes to zero, this ball of quantum states
 converges to a point representing the unique state consistent with the
 Born rule and Gleason's theorem.
\end_layout

