\begin_layout Standard
We next introduce probability axioms for IVPMs.
 First, for each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 we have the natural constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\ell\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

 that guarantees that every element of the interval can be interpreted as
 a conventional probability.
 We also include 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=[0,0]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=[1,1]$
\end_inset

 as limiting intervals to refer to the probability interval for impossible
 events and events that are certain.
 We can write this, respectively, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\emptyset)=\imposs$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\Omega)=\necess$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is the empty set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the event covering the entire sample space.
 For each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

, we also need the dual interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-r,1-\ell]$
\end_inset

 so that if one interval refers to the probability of an event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, the dual refers to the probability of the event's complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if we discover as a result of an experiment that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 for some event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\overline{E}\right)=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

 for the complementary event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition to these simple conditions, there are some subtle conditions
 on how intervals are combined, which we discuss next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two disjoint events with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[\ell_{1},r_{1}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[\ell_{2},r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 A first attempt at calculating the probability of the combined event that
 
\emph on
either
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 occurs might be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})=[\ell_{1}+\ell_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 In some cases, this is indeed a sensible definition.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[0.1,0.2]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[0.3,0.4]$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})=[0.4,0.6]$
\end_inset

.
 But consider an event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\overline{E}\right)=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

.
 The two events 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint; the naïve addition of intervals would give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E\cup\overline{E}\right)=[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

 which is not a valid probability interval.
 Moreover the event 
\begin_inset Formula $E\cup\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 is the entire space; its probability interval should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess$
\end_inset

 which is sharper than 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is that the two intervals are correlated: there is more information
 in the combined event than in each event separately so the combined event
 should be mapped to a sharper interval.
 In our example, even though the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 can be anywhere in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

