It is Meyer's great insight to realize that the Kochen-Specker theorem can
 be nullified by replacing the field of the reals by rational numbers.
 In other words, Meyer exclusively attributes finite-precision errors to
 the description of the states defined in a general Hilbert space.
 The response of Mermin, argues against Meyer's interpretation but accepts
 his framework.
 More generally, there have been responses that argue that the effect of
 finite-precision measurements on the Kochen-Specker theorem requires a
 different approach altogether (see for example Ax and Kochen's communication
 cited by Cabello
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cabello2002"

\end_inset

).
 Our approach is agnostic about attributing elements of reality to the state
 function (as Meyer did).
 We simply attribute lack of certainty to the uncertain results obtained
 through the use of a measuring instrument.
 Thus, the parameter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 in our framework reflects insufficient knowledge of the experimenter, which
 could be due to a variety of reasons related to imperfections of devices.
 For example, a typical question that an experimenter may not be able to
 answer accurately would be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

did an electron land in the left half or the right half of the screen?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 There are cases in which the electron would land too close to the middle
 of the screen for the experimenter to be able to determine with certainty
 that it was left or right of the center.
 We simply record this imprecision in the probability we assign to events,
 and use the axioms of probability theory to argue that a sharp transition
 occurs when the imprecision reaches a certain value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an experimental setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is calculated as follows.
 To determine the probability of any event, we typically repeat an experiment
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 times and count the number of times we witness the event.
 This assumes that for each run of the experiment we can determine, using
 our apparatus, whether the event occurred or not.
 Assume an event has an ideal mathematical probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, and we repeat the experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 times.
 In a perfect world we should be able to refute the event 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 times and calculate that the probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 We might also observe the event 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 times and refute it 
\begin_inset Formula $98$
\end_inset

 times and therefore calculate the probability to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this situation assumes perfect measurement conditions and remains
 within the context of conventional (real-valued) probability theory.
 The question we focus on is what happens if we are only able to refute
 it 
\begin_inset Formula $97$
\end_inset

 times and are 
\emph on
uncertain
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 times? This is quite common in actual experiments.
 Mathematically we can model this idea by stating that the probability of
 the event is in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0.03\right]$
\end_inset

 which says that the probability of the event could be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

 as each the three uncertain records could either be evidence for the event
 or against it.
 We just cannot nail it down given the current experimental results and
 therefore represent the evidence as a (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

-deterministic probability measure.
 The interesting observation is that the axioms of probability theory (like
 additivity and convexity) impose enough constraints on the structure of
 interval-valued quantum probability measures to make them robust in the
 face of small non-vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see this idea in the context of a quantum experiment, consider a three-dimens
ional Hilbert space with one-dimensional projectors
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, two-dimensional projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\rho}+P_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, and an experiment that is experiment repeated 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 times.
 By the Kochen-Specker theorem, it is impossible to build a probability
 measure that maps every projection to either 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\frac{0}{12}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\frac{12}{12}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the assignment
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 defined in Table
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:probability-measures"

\end_inset

 is not a QIVPM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider what happens if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

 of the data for 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 one-dimensional projector is uncertain.
 A potential account of this degradation is to assign to each event 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 the entire range of possibilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{1}(P)$
\end_inset

 as defined in Table
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:probability-measures"

\end_inset

.
 This measure is not a valid QIVPM because it does not satisfy the convexity
 condition: for any two orthogonal one-dimensional events 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

, the convexity condition requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{1}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)\subseteq\bar{\mu}_{1}\left(P_{0}\right)+\bar{\mu}_{1}\left(P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

